sentences: Maxted began his career in 1937 as a member of the Red Nichols big band, for which he wrote arrangements.
During 1947, he led a band with Ray Eberle and soon after led the Manhattan Jazz Band, which played Dixieland with Bob Zurke on boogie-woogie piano.
During the 1950s, he had a steady job as house pianist at Nick's club in Greenwich Village.
In 1958, British bandleader Reg Owen had a major hit on the American charts with Maxted's upbeat instrumental composition, "Manhattan Spiritual", released on the Palette label.
In the 1960s, he recorded for K&H and Liberty and as a sideman for Bob Crosby, Pee Wee Erwin, and Red Nichols.
He moved to Florida in the 1970s, and continued to play around Broward County for many years, including a years long stay at The Beach Club.
He died in Fort Lauderdale on October 11, 2001.
